[
    {
        "content": "<p>Let <code>C</code> be a 2-category, and let <code>x</code> be a distinguished object in <code>C</code>. </p>\n<p>What do you call it when <code>C(x,y)</code> has an initial object for all <code>y</code>?</p>\n<p>I almost want to say \"lax initial\" but it doesn't seem to be a lax limit.</p>",
        "id": 513974039,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Nicodemus",
        "timestamp": 1745447040
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This with the additional constraint that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mi>x</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{id}_x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8444em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">id</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is initial in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C(x, x)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is dual to what <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2002.06055\">Johnson and Yau (Definition 7.2.3)</a> call an inc-lax terminal object (inc stands for \"initial component\").</p>",
        "id": 513975344,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1745447745
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(So following their language it should be called inc-lax initial object)</p>",
        "id": 513975454,
        "sender_full_name": "Amar Hadzihasanovic",
        "timestamp": 1745447788
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, okay. Yeah. I'm realizing this is not unique up to equivalence.</p>",
        "id": 513975760,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Nicodemus",
        "timestamp": 1745447958
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There was a thread about this question ~2 or so years ago, <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/How.20is.20this.20.22initial.20object.22.20called.3F\">here</a>, and the conclusion that it indeed clashes with the terminology of a lax limit.</p>\n<p>In my <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.13001\">thesis</a> (Appendix E) I used the term <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/quasi-limit\">quasi-initial</a>, and unpacked this particular construction in detail</p>",
        "id": 514375187,
        "sender_full_name": "Bruno Gavranović",
        "timestamp": 1745586086
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Great! Thank you, Bruno. I am interested here in generalizing the result that if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>D</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G : D \\to C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> has a family of universal arrows <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>c</mi><mo>↦</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>d</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><msub><mi>η</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>:</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>G</mi><mi>c</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">c \\mapsto (d, \\eta_c : c\\to Gc)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.522em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">η</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0359em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">c</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> has a left adjoint, to quasi-universal arrows and lax adjunctions.</p>",
        "id": 514558894,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Nicodemus",
        "timestamp": 1745687994
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'll come back and discuss this later if time permits. A source/reference would be helpful but i'm probably still going to write it up myself as older papers are harder to search and reference, and you run into terminological clashes.</p>",
        "id": 514559006,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Nicodemus",
        "timestamp": 1745688054
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So, if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>D</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G : D\\to C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> is a pseudofunctor between bicategories, and for every <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">c</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span></span></span></span> in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> the oplax comma category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>c</mi><mo>↓</mo><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">c\\downarrow G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↓</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> has a quasi-initial object, then we can prove that all this gives rise in a canonical way to a colax functor <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C\\to D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span>. Intuitively this seems like a kind of \"left adjoint\" but if the quasi-initial objects aren't unique up to equivalence then neither will be the associated colax functor. I think that one needs to further assume some conditions which amount to forcing the \"left adjoint\" to be also pseudo rather than colax.</p>",
        "id": 514560879,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Nicodemus",
        "timestamp": 1745689506
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Somewhat annoyingly the condition I have in mind for uniqueness involves talking about <em>all</em> universal arrows into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span>, so it is really a property of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> rather than of any universal arrow into <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span>. I find this less elegant because it doesn't give the same sense of a theorem that shows local data can be uniquely glued into global data.</p>",
        "id": 514561060,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Nicodemus",
        "timestamp": 1745689662
    }
]